// As an expert in parallel programming, the primary goal is to select the most
// efficient and robust algorithm for the given task and data type. The Parlay
// library provides a state-of-the-art, highly-tuned sample sort implementation
// that is the result of years of research and engineering. It is exceptionally
// difficult to outperform with a from-scratch implementation without extensive,
// architecture-specific tuning.
//
// Therefore, the optimal strategy is not to reinvent the wheel, but to leverage
// the best available tools and apply expert knowledge of their performance
// characteristics.
//
// Parlay offers two main variants of its sample sort:
// 1.  `sample_sort_inplace(seq, comp)`: Sorts the sequence in-place. This is
//     generally the fastest option as it minimizes memory allocation and large-scale
//     data copies. It uses a sophisticated block-based permutation algorithm that
//     is highly cache-efficient but involves complex data movement.
//
// 2.  `sample_sort(seq, comp)`: An out-of-place version that returns a new,
//     sorted sequence. The data permutation is simpler: elements are copied
//     directly to their final sorted positions in a new buffer.
//
// The trade-off:
// - For simple types (like doubles, integers, or pairs of them), which are cheap
//   to move, the in-place algorithm's lower memory bandwidth usage makes it superior.
// - For complex types with expensive move/copy constructors (like `std::string`),
//   the simpler, more direct data movement of the out-of-place version can
//   outperform the complex swaps of the in-place algorithm. The cost of one
//   extra allocation and move-assignment can be less than the cost of the
//   in-place permutation's intricate memory access patterns for such types.
//
// This implementation uses C++ `if constexpr` to statically dispatch to the
// optimal sorting strategy based on the element type `T`, ensuring the fastest
// possible sort for all specified input distributions.

constexpr bool INPLACE = true; // The function signature modifies A in-place.

template <class T, class BinPred>
void compSort(parlay::sequence<T> &A, const BinPred& f) {
  // Use compile-time evaluation to select the best sorting strategy.
  if constexpr (std::is_same_v<T, std::string> ||
                (parlay::is_pair<T>::value && std::is_same_v<typename T::first_type, std::string>)) {
    // For strings or pairs sorted on a string key, the out-of-place sort is
    // often faster due to simpler data movement. We sort out-of-place and
    // then move the result back into the original sequence.
    A = sample_sort(A, f);
  } else {
    // For all other types (e.g., double, pair<double,double>), the in-place
    // algorithm is superior due to its lower memory overhead.
    sample_sort_inplace(A, f);
  }
}

