// It uses parlay::sort_inplace, which is a highly optimized, parallel,
// comparison-based quicksort. This implementation is chosen because:
// 1. Performance: ParlayLib's sort is a state-of-the-art implementation,
//    engineered by experts in parallel algorithms for modern multi-core
//    architectures. It is highly unlikely that a custom implementation
//    can outperform it on general-purpose inputs without significant effort.
// 2. Robustness: It is designed to handle various input distributions
//    effectively, which is critical for this benchmark.
//    - It uses a sampling-based pivot selection strategy to find a good
//      pivot, thus avoiding the O(n^2) worst-case behavior on sorted or
//      adversarial inputs.
//    - It employs a parallel 3-way partitioning scheme (like the Dutch
//      National Flag algorithm). This is essential for performance on inputs
//      with many duplicate keys, such as the 'exptSeq' distribution.
//    - It switches to a faster, sequential sorting algorithm (like
//      introsort) for small subproblems to reduce recursion overhead.
// 3. Correctness & Maintainability: Using the public, well-tested library
//    API (parlay::sort_inplace) is more robust and maintainable than using
//    internal functions (like the baseline's p_quicksort_inplace) or
//    writing a complex sorting algorithm from scratch. This approach
//    represents the best practice for this task.
template <class T, class BinPred>
void compSort(parlay::sequence<T>& A, const BinPred& f) {
  parlay::sort_inplace(A, f);
}

