template <class T, class BinPred>
void compSort(parlay::sequence<T> &A, const BinPred& f) {
  // The baseline uses parlay::internal::merge_sort_inplace. While effective,
  // the state-of-the-art for general-purpose parallel comparison sorting is
  // sample sort. Parlay's public-facing parlay::sort is a highly-optimized
  // implementation of sample sort.
  //
  // Why Sample Sort is Faster:
  // 1. Locality: The main parallel step, partitioning, involves linear scans
  //    of the data, which is very cache-friendly. Parallel merge sort, by
  //    contrast, has a merge step with less predictable memory access patterns.
  // 2. Scalability: Partitioning is embarrassingly parallel up to the point of
  //    permuting the data, leading to excellent scalability with many cores.
  // 3. Robustness: parlay::sort is engineered to handle skewed data and
  //    many duplicate keys (a weakness of simple quicksorts) by using
  //    oversampling and careful splitter selection.
  //
  // In-Place vs. Out-of-Place:
  // parlay::sort is an out-of-place algorithm, returning a new sorted sequence.
  // This is often faster than true in-place algorithms because it allows for
  // simpler logic and better memory access patterns (e.g., writing sorted
  // buckets contiguously to a destination buffer).
  //
  // To meet the required in-place function signature, we perform the
  // out-of-place sort and then move-assign the resulting sorted sequence
  // back to 'A'. parlay::sequence's move-assignment is a constant-time
  // operation that simply swaps internal pointers, making this final step
  // extremely cheap.
  //
  // parlay::make_slice(A) creates a non-owning view of the input sequence's
  // data. This is crucial to avoid making a full copy of 'A' before the
  // sorting even begins.
  A = parlay::sort(parlay::make_slice(A), f);
}

