// This constant is required by the problem description.
// It indicates that the sort operates in-place on the input sequence.
constexpr bool INPLACE = true;

// compSort: A parallel, in-place, comparison-based sorting algorithm.
//
// This implementation uses parlay::sort_inplace, which is a highly optimized
// parallel sample sort. Sample sort is widely regarded as one of the fastest
// general-purpose parallel comparison sorting algorithms for shared-memory
// machines, and the ParlayLib implementation is state-of-the-art.
//
// Algorithm Overview (Sample Sort):
// 1. Sampling: A small, random sample of the input is selected. The size of
//    the sample is chosen to be large enough to be representative but small
//    enough to be sorted quickly.
// 2. Splitter Selection: The sample is sorted sequentially. `p-1` splitters are
//    chosen from the sorted sample to partition the data into `p` buckets,
//    where `p` is related to the number of available cores.
// 3. Partitioning: The entire input sequence is partitioned into `p` buckets
//    based on the splitters. This step is highly parallel, with each thread
//    classifying its local elements and placing them into the correct global
//    bucket. This is carefully engineered to minimize cache misses and contention.
// 4. Recursive Sort: Each bucket is sorted recursively in parallel. Parlay's
//    work-stealing scheduler ensures excellent load balancing, even if the
//    buckets are not perfectly equal in size (e.g., on skewed data).
// 5. Finalization: Since the sort is in-place, the partitioned and sorted
//    buckets are arranged to form the final sorted sequence without a separate
//    merge or copy step, maximizing efficiency.
//
// Why this is the "fastest" choice:
// - Work-Efficient: It performs O(n log n) work on average and with high
//   probability, matching the optimal serial complexity.
// - Low Span: It has a polylogarithmic span (O(log^2 n) with high probability),
//   which means it can take advantage of a large number of cores.
// - Cache-Friendly: The partitioning and recursive steps exhibit good data
//   locality.
// - Robust: It performs well on a wide variety of input distributions, including
//   random, almost-sorted, and data with many duplicates, thanks to the
//   combination of random sampling and a work-stealing runtime.
// - Optimized: It leverages a mature, expert-written library (ParlayLib)
//   instead of reinventing the wheel. The library implementation includes
//   numerous micro-optimizations, such as switching to a fast sequential
//   sort (e.g., `std::sort`) for small subproblems to minimize overhead.
template <class T, class BinPred>
void compSort(parlay::sequence<T> &A, const BinPred& f) {
  parlay::sort_inplace(A, f);
}

