// 2. In parallel, each active vertex checks its active neighbors. If it has the
//    highest priority among them (with tie-breaking), it elects itself as a 'winner'
//    for this round.
// 3. All winning vertices are added to the MIS. Their flags are set to 1.
// 4. All neighbors of the winning vertices are removed from consideration for the MIS.
//    Their flags are set to 2. An atomic CAS is used here to safely handle cases
//    where an undecided vertex is a neighbor to multiple winners from this round.
// 5. The set of active vertices is rebuilt for the next round, containing only
//    vertices that are still undecided.
// 6. This process repeats until no vertices are active.
//
// This algorithm is lock-free (in the sense of not holding locks) and is guaranteed
// to terminate in O(log n) rounds with high probability. The total work is
// efficient, as the number of active vertices and edges decreases exponentially on average.
parlay::sequence<char> maximalIndependentSet(const Graph &G) {
  size_t n = G.n;
  auto Flags = parlay::sequence<char>::from_function(n, [](size_t) { return 0; });
  auto Active = parlay::tabulate(n, [](vertexId i) { return i; });
  auto P = parlay::sequence<uint64_t>(n);
  size_t round = 0;

  while (!Active.empty()) {
    round++;

